{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528218"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:39:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:39:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14275"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14275"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.62,0.01,0.04,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6970"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93057"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6970"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14275"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76410"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"387"},{"type":"tags","id":"477"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"1150"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16355"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31948"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41945"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43937"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/93057"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with confusion, agitation, and tremors. His partner reports that he has been a heavy drinker for many years but stopped drinking alcohol three days ago. He has a history of liver cirrhosis and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell and disorientated. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 160/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. He is diaphoretic and tremulous. He reports seeing small animals crawling on the walls and bed, and appears to be swatting at invisible insects. He is hypervigilant and startles easily at normal sounds. Neurological examination reveals mild ataxia and nystagmus. There is mild scleral icterus and palmar erythema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy","Delirium tremens","Acute psychosis","Alcohol withdrawal seizures","Hepatic encephalopathy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation in this case is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Edelirium tremens\u003C/strong\u003E, a severe form of alcohol withdrawal syndrome. Key features supporting this diagnosis include the timing of symptom onset (3 days after cessation of alcohol in a chronic heavy drinker), autonomic hyperactivity (tachycardia, hypertension, diaphoresis), and characteristic visual hallucinations (small animals) and perceptual disturbances (swatting at invisible insects, hypervigilance, and easily startled).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute psychosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with hallucinations and agitation, but it typically lacks the autonomic features and tremors seen in this patient. Moreover, the temporal relationship to alcohol cessation and the nature of the hallucinations (small moving objects) are more characteristic of delirium tremens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWernicke\u0027s encephalopathy\u003C/strong\u003E, while also associated with chronic alcoholism, typically presents with a triad of confusion, ataxia, and ophthalmoplegia. While this patient does show some neurological signs (ataxia and nystagmus), the acute onset and prominent autonomic features are more suggestive of delirium tremens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol withdrawal seizures\u003C/strong\u003E usually occur earlier in the withdrawal process, typically within 6-48 hours after the last drink. While seizures can be a component of delirium tremens, the overall clinical picture here is more consistent with fully developed delirium tremens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatic encephalopathy\u003C/strong\u003E can cause confusion and agitation in patients with liver disease, often due to chronic alcoholism. While this patient does have signs of liver disease (scleral icterus, palmar erythema), the severe autonomic features and characteristic hallucinations are more indicative of delirium tremens. Hepatic encephalopathy typically presents with a more gradual onset and lacks the severe autonomic features seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDelirium tremens is a medical emergency requiring immediate treatment, typically involving benzodiazepines for symptom control, thiamine supplementation, and close monitoring for complications such as electrolyte imbalances and seizures. The condition carries a significant mortality risk if not promptly recognised and treated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Delirium tremens typically occurs 48-96 hours after cessation of alcohol in chronic heavy drinkers.","Autonomic hyperactivity, such as tachycardia, hypertension, and diaphoresis, is a key feature of delirium tremens.","Visual hallucinations, particularly of small moving objects, are characteristic of delirium tremens."],"references":["Saunders JB, Latt N. Alcohol misuse and dependence. Assessment and management. Australian Family Physician. 2002 Dec;31(12):1079-85."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76410"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14275"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76410"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-20T15:04:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-20T15:04:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6970"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93057"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group"